al, ICC Women's World Cup Qualifying Series at Stellenbosch, Feb 24 2008], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 2020-03-07.</ref>\n|}\n\n==St George's Park, Post Elizabeth==\n{{main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at St George's Park}}\n\n==Tshwane University of Technology Oval, Pretoria==\nTwo five-wicket hauls have been taken at [[Tshwane University of Technology Oval]], both in the same women's One Day International. After being used during the [[2005 Women's Cricket World Cup]] the ground has not been used for international cricket since 2005.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/23/1651.html Tshwane University of Technology Oval, Pretoria], CricketArchive. Retrieved 2020-03-07. {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Five-wicket hauls in Women's One Day Internationals at Tshwane University of Technology Oval\n|-\n! No.\n! Bowler\n! Date\n! Team\n! Opposing Team\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|Inn\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|O\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|R\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|W\n! Result\n|-\n| 1 || [[Neetu David]]{{efn-ua|name=innz05|David and Milliken took their five-wicket hauls in the same ODI.}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2005|3|30}}{{efn|name=wc05|This match was part of the [[2005 Women's Cricket World Cup]].}} || {{crw|IND}} || {{crw|NZ}} || 1 || 10 || 32 || 5 || New Zealand won<ref name=wodi526>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8584/game/67381/india-women-vs-new-zealand-women-19th-match-womens-world-cup-2004-05 19th Match, Women's World Cup at Pretoria, Mar 30 2005], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 2020-03-07.</ref>\n|-\n| 2 || [[Louise Milliken]]{{efn-ua|name=innz05}} || {{dts|format=dmy|2005|3|30}}{{efn|name=wc05}} || {{crw|NZ}} || {{crw|IND}} || 2 || 10 || 25 || 5 || New Zealand won<ref name=wodi526/>\n|}\n\n==Wanderers Stadium, Johannesburg==\n{{main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at the Wanderers}}\n\n==Willowmoore Park, Benoni==\n{{updated|7 March 2020}}\nA single five-wicket haul has been taken in international cricket at [[Willowmoore Park]] since the ground was first used for One Day Internationals in 1997.<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/ground/59039.html Willowmoore Park], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 2020-03-07.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Five-wicket hauls in Men's One Day Internationals at Willowmoore Park\n|-\n! No.\n! Bowler\n! Date\n! Team\n! Opposing Team\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|Inn\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|O\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|R\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|W\n! Result\n|-\n| 1 || [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] || {{dts|format=dmy|1998|4|15}} || {{cr|SL}} || {{cr|PAK}} || 2 || 9.2 || 23 || 5 || Sri Lanka won<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8553/game/66085/pakistan-vs-sri-lanka-7th-match-standard-bank-international-one-day-series-1997-98 7th Match, Standard Bank International One-Day Series at Benoni, Apr 15 1998], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 2020-03-07.</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=11;filter=advanced;host=3;orderby=start;size=200;template=results;type=bowling;view=innings;wicketsmin1=5;wicketsval1=wickets International five-wicket hauls on South African grounds], [[CricInfo]]\n\n{{International cricket five-wicket hauls by ground}}\n\n[[Category:South African cricket lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of international cricket five-wicket hauls by ground|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use South African English|date=March 2019}}\nThe [[South Africa national cricket team]] played its first representative match in 1889 against a [[English cricket team in South Africa in 1888\u201389|touring side of English players]] organised by [[Robert Warton (umpire)|Major RG Wharton]]. In 1897 the two representative matches on the tour were retrospectively awarded [[Test cricket]] status, South Africa becoming the third Test playing country.{{efn|No first-class cricket had been played in South Africa prior to these matches. As a result, the first Test match played in the country was also the first first-class match played.}}<ref>[[John Major|Major J]] (2007) ''More Than A Game'', p.201. London: HarperCollins. {{isbn|978-0-00-718364-7}}</ref><ref>Williamson M (2009) [https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22743939/the-ignorant-internationals The ignorant internationals], [[CricInfo]], 2009-11-28. Retrieved 2020-03-09.</ref> The team played regularly against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], [[England cricket team|England]] and [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] until the 1960s but played no matches against sides from countries such as [[India national cricket team|India]] or [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] due to the racially exclusive policies of successive South African governments which barred non-white players from international cricket. This evolved into a formal policy of [[apartheid]] in the late 1940s and by the end of the 1960s pressure had grown on other countries not to play South African sporting sides. \n\nThe 1968 [[D'Oliveira affair]] created significant tension between South Africa and England and the South African tour of England in 1970 was cancelled following pressure from anti-apartheid campaigners.<ref name=ci16dec13>[[Ashley Mallett|Mallett A]] (2013) [https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21582524/madiba-godfather Madiba and the godfather], [[CricInfo]], 2013-12-13. Retrieved 2020-03-14.</ref> In 1971 [[Don Bradman]], the chair of the [[Australian Cricket Board]], refused to allow the South African team to tour Australia, having met with South African Prime Minister [[John Vorster]] whose views on race had disturbed Bradman.<ref name=ci16dec13/><ref>Burgmann M (2008) [https://www.smh.com.au/sport/the-day-apartheid-was-hit-for-six-20080823-gdss3b.html The day apartheid was hit for six], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 2008-08-23. Retrieved 2020-03-14.</ref> The subsequent [[sporting boycott of South Africa]] isolated South African cricket, with the last international tour of the country in 1972 when New Zealand's women visited the country. The sporting boycott lasted until the fall of the apartheid regime and South Africa next played international cricket in 1991, touring West Indies. The first tour of the country following the lifting of the boycott took place in 1992, [[India national cricket team|India]] playing a series in the country for the first time.\n\nIn [[cricket]], a [[five-wicket haul]] (also known as a \"five-for\" or \"fifer\") refers to a [[Bowler (cricket)|bowler]] taking five or more [[wicket]]s in a single [[Innings#Cricket|innings]]. This is regarded as a notable achievement.<ref>Pervez MA (2001) ''A Dictionary of Cricket'', p.31. Hyderabad: Sangam Books (India). {{isbn|978-81-7370-184-9}}</ref> This article details the five-wicket hauls taken on South African cricket grounds in official international Test, One Day International and Twenty20 International matches.{{efn|In the 1980s, during the sporting boycott, there were several [[rebel tour]]s of South Africa by teams made up of players from England, Sri Lanka, West Indies and Australia, all of which played against representative South African sides. These are not classed as official international matches and five-wicket hauls taken in them are not included in this article.}}\n\nThe first five-wicket hauls in international cricket in South Africa were taken during the first Test match at [[St George's Park Cricket Ground]] in 1889. [[England cricket team|England's]] [[C. Aubrey Smith|Aubrey Smith]] took the first with South Africa's [[Albert Rose-Innes]] also taking a five-wicket haul later in the same match. In One Day International cricket, the first five-wicket haul in South Africa was taken in 1992 in the first ODI played in the country by future South African captain [[Hansie Cronje]], whilst [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistani]] bowler [[Umar Gul]] took the first in [[Twenty20 International]] cricket in the country.\n\n==Key==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Symbol\n! Meaning\n|-\n|'''Date'''\n|Date the [[Test cricket|Test]] started or [[One Day International|ODI]]/[[Twenty20 International|T20I]] was held\n|-\n|'''Inn'''\n|[[Innings#Cricket|Innings]] in which five-wicket haul was taken\n|-\n|'''O'''\n|Number of [[Over (cricket)|overs]] bowled\n|-\n|'''R'''\n|Number of [[Run (cricket)|runs]] conceded\n|-\n|'''W'''\n|Number of [[Wicket (dismissal)|wickets]] taken\n|-\n|'''Result'''\n|[[Result (cricket)|Result]] of the match\n|}\n\n==Boland Park, Paarl==\n{{updated|7 March 2020}}\nTwo five-wicket hauls have been taken at [[Boland Park]], both in men's One Day Internationals. The ground was first used for international cricket in 1997.<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/ground/59147.html Boland Park], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 2020-03-07.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Five-wicket hauls in Men's One Day Internationals at Boland Park\n|-\n! No.\n! Bowler\n! Date\n! Team\n! Opposing Team\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|Inn\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|O\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|R\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|W\n! Result\n|-\n| 1 || [[Eddo Brandes]] || {{dts|format=dmy|1997|1|27}} || {{cr|ZIM}} || {{cr|IND}} || 2 || 9.5 || 41 || 5  || [[Result (cricket)#Tie|Tie]]<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8553/game/66070/india-vs-zimbabwe-3rd-match-standard-bank-international-one-day-series-1996-97 3rd Match (D/N), Standard Bank International One-Day Series at Paarl, Jan 27 1997], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 2020-03-07.</ref>\n|-\n| 2 || [[Lasith Malinga]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2012|1|11}} || {{cr|SL}} || {{cr|SA}} || 1 || 10 || 54 || 5 || South Africa won<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/12644/game/514035/south-africa-