8\n| align=center |  [[St Mary's College, Dundalk]]\n| align=center | 4-06\n| align=center | 0-04\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]\n| align=center | Dundalk\n| align=center | \n| align=center |  \n|-\n| align=center | 1937\n| align=center | [[St Patrick's College, Cavan]]<sup>(3)</sup>\n| align=center | 2-06\n| align=center | 1-06\n| align=center | [[St Mary's College, Dundalk]]\n| align=center | Breffni Park\n| align=center | \n| align=center | \n|-\n| align=center | 1936\n| align=center | [[St Patrick's College, Cavan]]<sup>(2)</sup>\n| align=center | 3-03\n| align=center | 1-07\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]\n| align=center | Monaghan\n| align=center | \n| align=center | \n|-\n| align=center |  1935\n| align=center |  [[St Patrick's College, Cavan]]\n| align=center | 7-11\n| align=center | 0-00\n| align=center | [[Monaghan CBS]]\n| align=center | Breffni Park\n| align=center | \n| align=center | T Canning\n|-\n| align=center | 1934\n| align=center | [[St Macartan's College|St. Macartan's College, Monaghan]]<sup>(5)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1933\n| align=center |[[St Macartan's College|St. Macartan's College, Monaghan]]<sup>(4)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1932\n| align=center | [[St Macartan's College|St. Macartan's College, Monaghan]]<sup>(3)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1931\n| align=center |[[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(8)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center |1930\n| align=center |[[St Macartan's College|St. Macartan's College, Monaghan]]<sup>(2)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center |1929\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(7)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1928\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(6)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1927\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(5)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1926\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(4)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center | 1925\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(3)</sup><br>[[St Macartan's College|St. Macartan's College, Monaghan]]<br>[[St. Malachy's College|St. Malachy's, Belfast]]\n|-\n| align=center | 1924\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(2)</sup>\n|-\n| align=center |  1923\n| align=center | [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]<sup>(2)</sup>\n|-\n|}\n\n* The [[Iggy Jones|Iggy Jones]] Man of the Match trophy has only been awarded to players on the losing side on three occasions.  [[Martin Clarke|Martin Clarke]] and Joe Ireland for [[St Louis, Kilkeel]] in consecutive finals, and Colm Greenan for St Macartan's Monaghan.\n* [[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]] made their final debut in 1976, and then went on to feature in every final until 1986. They won 6 and lost 5 of those finals.\n* [[St Colman's College, Newry]] and [[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]] dominated the competition between 1975 and 1991, with at least one of the schools featuring in the final.  The schools won 14 titles in 17 years, including every title between 1975 and 1985.\n* [[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]] didn't win a final against their illustrious rivals until 1989.  [[St Colman's College, Newry]] won the first 5 finals ('76, '78,'79, '81, and '89) between the two sides.\n* Between 1988 and 1990 [[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]] and [[St Colman's College, Newry]] played 6 MacRory finals.  The 1988 final went to a second replay and the 1990 final went to a replay\n* The MacRory Cup had first time winners in 2017 [[St Mary's Grammar School|St. Mary's Grammar School, Magherafelt]] and 2018 St Ronan's Lurgan. Prior to that the compeition did not have a first time winner since [[St. Patrick's Academy, Dungannon]]'s victory in 1991\n*[[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]](1950-52), [[St. Michael's College (Enniskillen)|St. Michael's, Enniskillen]] (1968-70) and [[St Colman's College, Newry]] (1989-91) are the only schools to have lost 3 consecutive finals.\n\n==Longest winning streaks==\n*[[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]] won 7 consecutive MacRory Cups (One Shared), when the winners were decided on a league basis.\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Team'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Streak'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Years'''\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]\n| align=center |4\n|1944\u20131947\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]]\n| align=center |4\n|1982\u20131985\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's College, Cavan]]\n| align=center |3\n|1935\u20131937\n|-\n|[[St Colman's College, Newry]]\n| align=center |3\n|1967\u20131969\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]]\n| align=center |3\n|1994\u20131996\n|}\n\n== Most Common Finals==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Teams'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Finals'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Years'''\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]] v [[St Colman's College, Newry]]\n| align=center |11\n|1976, 1978, 1979, 1981, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1993, 1995, 1998, 2020\n|-\n|[[St. Michael's College, Enniskillen]] v [[Christian Brothers Grammar School, Omagh|Omagh Christian Brothers Grammar School]]\n| align=center |5\n|2019, 2002, 2001, 1974, 1973\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]] v [[Abbey Christian Brothers' Grammar School|Abbey Christian Brothers Grammar School, Newry]]\n| align=center |4\n|1983, 1982, 1980, 1977\n|-\n|[[St Colman's College, Newry]] v [[St. Patrick's College, Cavan]]\n| align=center |4\n|1975, 1963, 1960, 1958\n|-\n|[[St Colman's College, Newry]] v [[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]\n| align=center |4\n|1967, 1957, 1950, 1945\n|}\n\n== Longest Gap Between Title Victories==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Team'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Years'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Difference'''\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]]\n| align=center |1953-2000\n| align=center |47 years\n|-\n|[[St. Patrick's College, Cavan]]\n| align=center |1972-2015\n| align=center |43 years\n|-\n|[[Christian Brothers Grammar School, Omagh|Omagh Christian Brothers Grammar School]]\n| align=center |1974-2001\n| align=center |27 years\n|-\n|[[Abbey Christian Brothers' Grammar School|Abbey Christian Brothers Grammar School, Newry]]\n| align=center |1987-2006\n| align=center |19 years\n|}\n\n\n\n==Noted footballers==\n* [[Oisin McConville]] played for [[St Patrick's Grammar School, Armagh]].\n* [[Dermot McNicholl]] played in five MacRory Cup finals in the early 1980s with [[St. Patrick's College, Maghera]]. Winning four titles and was twice the victorious captain.\n* [[Martin Clarke]] produced a number of memorable displays in 2005 and captained his school [[St Louis, Kilkeel]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.stlouis.org.uk/news/macrory/2004_2005/matchreport.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061015072034/http://www.stlouis.org.uk/news/macrory/2004_2005/matchreport.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-10-15 |title=Mourne Spirit Triumphs as St Louis Lose out on MacRory Title |author=Steven McVeigh |publisher=St Louis Grammar School }}</ref>\n* [[Michael Murphy (Gaelic footballer)|Michael Murphy]] played for [[St Eunan's College]], reaching the 2008 semi-final.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan|last=Ferry|title=St Eunan's College take on Patrician in MacRory play-off|work=[[Donegal News]]|date=30 January 2020|page=73}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n; Schools' Senior A Football\n* [[Hogan Cup|Hogan Cup (All-Ireland Championship)]]\n* [[Connacht Colleges Senior Football Championship|Aonghus Murphy Memorial Cup (Connacht Championship)]]\n* [[Leinster Colleges Senior Football Championship|Brother Bosco Cup (Leinster Championship)]]\n* [[Corn U\u00ed Mhuir\u00ed|Corn U\u00ed Mhuir\u00ed (Munster Championship)]]\n\n; Schools' Senior A Hurling\n* [[Dr. Croke Cup|Dr. Croke Cup (All-Ireland Championship)]]\n* [[Leinster Colleges Senior Hurling Championship|Leinster Championship]]\n*[[Dr. Harty Cup|Dr. Harty Cup (Munster Championship)]]\n\n; Schools' Senior B Hurling\n* [[Mageean Cup| Mageean Cup (Ulster Championship)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|url=http://www.danskebankulsterschoolsgaa.com/competitions/macrory-mccormack-cup-1819/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macrory Cup}}\n[[Category:Gaelic football competitions in Ulster]]\n[[Category:Gaelic football cup competitions]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacRory_Cup"}
{"title_page": "NIOSH air filtration rating", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. rating of respirators such as face masks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:N95mask.jpg|thumb|A filtering facepiece N95 [[dust mask]]]]\n[[File:P100_ovm_respirator.jpg|thumb|Half-face air-purifying respirator with combination P100 particulate filter (magenta) and organic vapor (black) cartridge]]\n[[File:WTC search.jpg|thumb|A [[firefighter]] wearing an N95 dust mask]]\n\nThe '''NIOSH air filtration rating''' is the U.S. [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] (NIOSH)'s classification of filtering [[Respirator|respirators]]. The ratings describe the ability of the device to protect the wearer from dust and liquid droplets in the air. The certification and approval process for respiratory protective devices is governed by Part 84 of Title 42 of the [[Code of Federal Regulations]] (42 CFR 84).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/retrieveECFR?gp=&SID=c9c15fd462ffe5c4f4e85b73f161b2e0&r=PART&n=42y1.0.1.7.67#se42.1.84_11|title=42 CFR Part 84 - Approval of Respiratory Protective Devices|last=|first=|date=February 6, 2020|website=ecfr.gov |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Respiratory protective devices so classified include [[Respirator|air-purifying respirators]] (APR) such as filtering facepiece respirators ([[dust mask]]s) and chemical protective cartridges that have incorporated particulate filter elements. \n\nThe classifications only cover the filtration of particles or [[Aerosol|aerosols]], not the air-purifying respirator's ability to remove chemical gasses and vapors from air, which is regulated under 42 CFR 84 Subpart L. For more information see [[Cartridge (respirator)]]. The classifications assume that the [[Respirator fit test|respirator is properly fitted]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2017/11/02/noshave/|title=To Beard or not to Beard? That\u2019s a good Question! |date=2 November 2017 |work=NIOSH Science Blog |publisher=CDC|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== NIOSH classifications ==\n{{See also|Respirator#United States norms}}\n\nNIOSH has currently established nine classifications of approved particulate filtering respirators based on a combination of the respirator series and efficiency level. The first part of the filter's classification indicates the series using the letters N, R, or P to indicate the filter's resistance to filtration efficiency degradation when exposed to oil-based aerosols (e.g., lubricants, cutting fluids, glycerine, etc.).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/npptl/topics/respirators/disp_part/respsource1quest2.html|title=Respirator Trusted-Source Information Section 1: NIOSH-Approved Respirators|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2018|website=The National Personal Protective Technology Laboratory (NPPTL)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/96-101/default.html|title=NIOSH Guide to the Selection and Use of Particulate Respirators|last=|first=|date=June 6, 2014|website=The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|orig-year=January 1996|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Definitions and intended use for each series is indicated below.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/dts/osta/otm/otm_viii/otm_viii_2.html#app_viii:2_4|title=OSHA Technical Manual Section 8VII: Chapter 2 Respiratory Protection Appendix 2-4|last=|first=|date=|website=OSHA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020|edition=TED 01-00-015}}</ref>\n\n* N for '''N'''ot resistant to oil. Used when oil particulates are not present.\n* R for '''R'''esistant to oil. Used when oil particulates are present and the filter is disposed of after one shift.\n* P for oil '''P'''roof. Used when oil particulates are present and the filter is re-used for more than one shift.\n\nThe second value indicates the minimum efficiency level of the filter. When tested according to the protocol established by NIOSH each filter classification must demonstrate the minimum efficiency level indicated below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+NIOSH Particulate Respirator Class Minimum Efficiency Levels<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Respirator\nClass\n!Minimum\nEfficiency Level\n|-\n|[[N95 mask|N95]], R95, P95\n|95%\n|-\n|N99, R99, P99\n|99%\n|-\n|N100, R100, P100\n|99.97%\n|}\nSince filters are tested against the most penetrating particle size of 0.3 [[micrometre|\u03bcm]] an APR with a P100 classification would be at least 99.97% efficient at removing particles of this size.<ref name=\":1\" /> Particles with a size both less than and greater than 0.3 \u03bcm are filtered at an efficiency greater than 99.97%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/96-101/appendices.html|title=NIOSH Guide to the Selection and Use of Particulate Respirators Appendix E: Commonly Asked Questions and Answers About Part 84 Respirators|last=|first=|date=June 6, 2014|website=The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Although it is counter-intuitive that particle sizes of less than 0.3 \u03bcm are filtered with a greater efficiency, the forces which have the greatest impact on the effectiveness of filtration ([[aerosol impaction]], interception, and [[Diffusion (aerosol physics)|diffusion]]) are weakest at this size for filters tested by NIOSH.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2003-136/pdfs/2003-136.pdf?id=10.26616/NIOSHPUB2003136|title=Guidance for Filtration and Air-Cleaning Systems to Protect Building Environments from Airborne Chemical, Biological, or Radiological Attacks|publisher=[[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]|year=April 2003|isbn=|location=Cincinnati, OH|pages=8-12|access-date=February 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A filter's collection efficiency for particle sizes other than those for which it is least efficient is indicated by the filter's efficiency curve. \n[[File:Filteration_Collection_Mechanisms.png|alt=|none|thumb|400x400px|Classic collection efficiency curve with filter collection mechanisms]]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Respirator#European norms|European respirator standards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Air pollution]]\n[[Category:National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Respirators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S. rating of respirators such as face masks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:N95mask.jpg|thumb|A filtering facepiece N95 [[dust mask]]]]\n[[File:P100_ovm_respirator.jpg|thumb|Half-face air-purifying respirator with combination P100 particulate filter (magenta) and organic vapor (black) cartridge]]\n[[File:WTC search.jpg|thumb|A [[firefighter]] wearing an N95 dust mask]]\n\nThe '''NIOSH air filtration rating''' is the U.S. [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] (NIOSH)'s classification of filtering [[Respirator|respirators]]. The ratings describe the ability of the device to protect the wearer from dust and liquid droplets in the air. The certification and approval process for respiratory protective devices is governed by Part 84 of Title 42 of the [[Code of Federal Regulations]] (42 CFR 84).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/retrieveECFR?gp=&SID=c9c15fd462ffe5c4f4e85b73f161b2e0&r=PART&n=42y1.0.1.7.67#se42.1.84_11|title=42 CFR Part 84 - Approval of Respiratory Protective Devices|last=|first=|date=February 6, 2020|website=ecfr.gov |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Respiratory protective devices so classified include [[Respirator|air-purifying respirators]] (APR) such as filtering facepiece respirators ([[dust mask]]s) and chemical protective cartridges that have incorporated particulate filter elements. \n\nThe classifications only cover the filtration of particles or [[Aerosol|aerosols]], not the air-purifying respirator's ability to remove chemical gasses and vapors from air, which is regulated under 42 CFR 84 Subpart L. For more information see [[Cartridge (respirator)]]. The classifications assume that the [[Respirator fit test|respirator is properly fitted]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2017/11/02/noshave/|title=To Beard or not to Beard? That\u2019s a good Question! |date=2 November 2017 |work=NIOSH Science Blog |publisher=CDC|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== NIOSH classifications ==\n{{See also|Respirator#United States norms}}\n\nNIOSH has currently established nine classifications of approved particulate filtering respirators based on a combination of the respirator series and efficiency level. The first part of the filter's classification indicates the series using the letters N, R, or P to indicate the filter's resistance to filtration efficiency degradation when exposed to oil-based aerosols (e.g., lubricants, cutting fluids, glycerine, etc.).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/npptl/topics/respirators/disp_part/respsource1quest2.html|title=Respirator Trusted-Source Information Section 1: NIOSH-Approved Respirators|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2018|website=The National Personal Protective Technology Laboratory (NPPTL)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/96-101/default.html|title=NIOSH Guide to the Selection and Use of Particulate Respirators|last=|first=|date=June 6, 2014|website=The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|orig-year=January 1996|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Definitions and intended use for each series is indicated below.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/dts/osta/otm/otm_viii/otm_viii_2.html#app_viii:2_4|title=OSHA Technical Manual Section 8VII: Chapter 2 Respiratory Protection Appendix 2-4|last=|first=|date=|website=OSHA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020|edition=TED 01-00-015}}</ref>\n\n* N for '''N'''ot resistant to oil. Used when oil particulates are not present.\n* R for '''R'''esistant to oil. Used when oil particulates are present and the filter is disposed of after one shift.\n* P for oil '''P'''roof. Used when oil particulates are present and the filter is re-used for more than one shift.\n\nThe second value indicates the minimum efficiency level of the filter. When tested according to the protocol established by NIOSH each filter classification must demonstrate the minimum efficiency level indicated below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+NIOSH Particulate Respirator Class Minimum Efficiency Levels<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Respirator\nClass\n!Minimum\nEfficiency Level\n|-\n|[[N95 mask|N95]], R95, P95\n|95%\n|-\n|N99, R99, P99\n|99%\n|-\n|N100, R100, P100\n|99.97%\n|}\nSince filters are tested against the most penetrating particle size of 0.3 [[micrometre|\u03bcm]] an APR with a P100 classification would be at least 99.97% efficient at removing particles of this size.<ref name=\":1\" /> Particles with a size both less than and greater than 0.3 \u03bcm are filtered at an efficiency greater than 99.97%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/96-101/appendices.html|title=NIOSH Guide to the Selection and Use of Particulate Respirators Appendix E: Commonly Asked Questions and Answers About Part 84 Respirators|last=|first=|date=June 6, 2014|website=The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Although it is counter-intuitive that particle sizes of less than 0.3 \u03bcm are filtered with a greater efficiency, the forces which have the greatest impact on the effectiveness of filtration ([[aerosol impaction]], interception, and diffusion) are weakest at this size for filters tested by NIOSH.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2003-136/pdfs/2003-136.pdf?id=10.26616/NIOSHPUB2003136|title=Guidance for Filtration and Air-Cleaning Systems to Protect Building Environments from Airborne Chemical, Biological, or Radiological Attacks|publisher=[[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]|year=April 2003|isbn=|location=Cincinnati, OH|pages=8-12|access-date=February 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A filter's collection efficiency for particle sizes other than those for which it is least efficient is indicated by the filter's efficiency curve. \n[[File:Filteration_Collection_Mechanisms.png|alt=|none|thumb|400x400px|Classic collection efficiency curve with filter collection mechanisms]]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Respirator#European norms|European respirator standards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Air pollution]]\n[[Category:National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Respirators]]\n", "name_user": "CRGreathouse", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNIOSH classifications:link to deposition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NIOSH_air_filtration_rating"}
{"title_page": "List of awards and nominations received by Jennifer Aniston", "text_new": "{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em; text-align: left; font-size: 90%; vertical-align: middle;\"\n|+ <span style=\"font-size: 9pt\">'''[[Jennifer Aniston]] awards and nominations'''</span>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:JenniferAnistonHWoFFeb2012.jpg|center|252px]] {{Small|Aniston at a ceremony to receive a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] on February 22, 2012}}\n|- bgcolor=#D9E8FF style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!style=\"vertical-align: middle;\"| Award\n| style=\"background:#cceecc; font-size:8pt;\" width=\"60px\"| Wins\n| style=\"background:#eecccc; font-size:8pt;\" width=\"60px\"| Nominations\n|- bgcolor=#eeeeff\n|align=\"center\" | [[Critics Choice Award]]s\n|{{won|0}}\n|{{nom|1}}\n|- bgcolor=#eeeeff\n|align=\"center\" | [[Directors Guild of America Award]]s\n|{{won|0}}\n|{{nom|1}}\n|- bgcolor=#eeeeff\n|align=\"center\"| [[Golden Globe Award]]s\n|{{won|1}}\n|{{nom|5}}\n|- bgcolor=#eeeeff\n|align=\"center\"| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s\n|{{won|1}}\n|{{nom|6}}\n|- bgcolor=#eeeeff\n|align=\"center\" | [[Satellite Award]]s\n|{{won|0}}\n|{{nom|3}}\n|- bgcolor=#eeeeff\n|align=\"center\"| [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s\n|{{won|2}}\n|{{nom|11}}\n|}\n\n[[Jennifer Aniston]] has been honored with numerous accolades throughout her career. She has received nominations for six [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, five [[Golden Globe Awards]], and eleven [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s. She also received a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion picture star]] on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\n\nFor her role in the sitcom ''[[Friends]]'', Aniston won the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] in 1996, [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] in 2002, and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] in 2003. She earned a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination in 2009 for her guest starring role on the sitcom ''[[30 Rock]]''. For her performance in the 2014 drama film ''[[Cake (2014 film)|Cake]]'', she received [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Golden Globe Award]] nominations. For her performance in the [[Apple TV+]] drama series ''[[The Morning Show (American TV series)|The Morning Show]]'', she received two Golden Globe Award nominations and won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series|Screen Actors Guild Award]].\n\n== Major Awards ==\n\n=== [[Directors Guild of America Award|Directors Guild Awards]] ===\nThe Directors Guild Awards are issued by the '''Directors Guild of America'''.\n\n'''0 wins''' of 1 nomination\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:39em;\"| Nominated work\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:39em;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[64th Directors Guild of America Awards|2012]]\n|''[[Five (TV movie)|Five]]''\n|[[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 Miniseries or TV Film|Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Movies for Television/Miniseries]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dga.org/Awards/History/2010s/2011.aspx?value=2011|website=www.dga.org|access-date=2019-05-10|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323131239/http://www.dga.org/Awards/History/2010s/2011.aspx?value=2011|archive-date=2019-03-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== [[Golden Globe Award]]s ===\nThe Golden Globe Awards are issued by the [[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] (HFPA).\n\n'''1 win''' of 5 nominations\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:39em;\"| Nominated work\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:39em;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[59th Golden Globe Awards|2002]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Friends]]''\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2002|title=Winners & Nominees 2002|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208070744/https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2002|archive-date=2017-12-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[60th Golden Globe Awards|2003]]\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]]\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2003|title=Winners & Nominees 2003|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120313/https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2003|archive-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[72nd Golden Globe Awards|2015]]\n|''[[Cake (2014 film)|Cake]]''\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2015|title=Winners & Nominees 2015|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410165726/https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2015|archive-date=2019-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|