Wrong Place|website=www.charitywatch.org|language=en|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.islandpacket.com/news/local/community/beaufort-news/article33646743.html|title=Beaufort big cat owner has fraud conviction on his record |last=Lurye|first=Rebecca|date=April 30, 2015|website=www.islandpacket.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in February 2016, shortly before its founder, [[Joe Exotic]], attempted to hire a hitman to kill [[Carole Baskin]], Chief Executive Officer of [[Big Cat Rescue]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Garcia |first=Sandra E. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/22/us/joe-exotic-sentence-oklahoma.html |title=Former Zookeeper Sentenced to 22 Years in Murder-for-Hire Plot |date=January 22, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=February 27, 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> who had won a lawsuit against him in 2013.<ref name=\"Beast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|last=Williams|first=Sean|date=June 22, 2019|website=www.thedailybeast.com}}</ref><ref name=\"oklahoman2019\">{{cite news|first=Nolan|last=Clay|title=Joe Exotic found guilty in murder-for-hire case|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5627553/joe-exotic-found-guilty-in-murder-for-hire-case|work=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=April 3, 2019|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news |title='Joe Exotic' sentenced to 22 years in federal prison on murder-for-hire, wildlife charges |url=https://www.koco.com/article/joe-exotic-to-be-formally-sentenced-on-murder-for-hire-wildlife-charges/30625982 |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |website=ABC Koco News 5 |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Establishment and history ==\n[[File:Taliger at G.W. Park.jpg|thumb|right|[[Tiliger]] at the G. W. Zoo, pictured in 2013]]\nThe Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park is situated on {{convert|16|acre}} and began as a shelter for endangered and exotic species of animals. The zoo was home to over 50 species of animals and 200 big cats, such as [[Tiger|tigers]], [[Lion|lions]], [[Puma (genus)|puma]], [[liger]]s and [[tigon]]s. The zoo was dedicated to Exotic\u2019s brother Garold Wayne, who died in a car crash with a drunk driver in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5807284/tiger-king-netflix-true-story/?amp=true|title=The Wild Story Behind Netflix\u2019s New Docuseries Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|date=March 20, 2020|last=Gajanan|first=Mahita|website=www.time.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal problems ===\nBetween February and June 2006, PETA had an investigator work as an employee.<ref>{{cite web|last=Surette|first=Rusty| url=http://www.news9.com/story/13825476/alleged-peta-member-planted-at-exotic-animal-park-under-criminal-investigation?redirected=true|title=PETA Allegedly Paid Man To 'Spy, Download Information' From Exotic Animal Park|date=January 11, 2011|accessdate= July 28, 2011}}</ref> PETA's undercover investigator made footage which the group released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta.org/videos/misery-and-cruelty-at-g-w-exotic-animals-memorial-park-in-oklahoma-a-peta-investigation/|title=Misery and Cruelty at G.W. Exotic Animals Memorial Park in Oklahoma: A PETA Investigation |publisher=People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals |date= |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> PETA alleged that animals were starved and  \"routinely hit, punched, kicked, sprayed with cold water, and struck with rakes and shovels.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta.org/features/gw-investigator-log-neglect.aspx |title=G.W. Exotic Animal Memorial Park Investigator's Log\u2014Neglect |publisher=People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals |date= |accessdate=June 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta.org/features/gw/|title=Oklahoma Pseudo-Sanctuary: Shelter From Danger or Dangerous Shelter? |publisher=People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals |date= |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2012, the [[Humane Society of the United States]] released video taken by an undercover investigator. It included footage of a tiger being dragged across gravel, big cats being hit and Exotic instructing staff to smack cubs to make them walk.<ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/alleged-abuse-at-gw-exotic-animal-park-seen-on-tape/|title=Alleged abuse at GW Memorial Park seen on tape|date=May 16, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"humdes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.humanesociety.org/news/press_releases/2012/05/ok_exotics_investigation.html|title='If they walk in here and take my animals away, it's going to be a small Waco':Joe Exotics pledge after being accused|date=May 16, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref> HSUS claimed that 5 tigers died during their investigation, one of which did not receive veterinary care.<ref name=\"humdes\" />\nIn May 2014, the USDA cited the park for failure to provide adequate veterinary care. According to officials, an injured bear's wound reopened and an employee attempted to stitch it. The injury subsequently worsened and the bear was euthanized.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kxii.com/home/headlines/GW-Interactive-Zoological-Park-under-fire-for-alleged-animal-mistreatment-260343581.html|title=G.W. Interactive Zoological Park under fire for alleged animal mistreatment|date=May 22, 2014|accessdate=May 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFeeding big cats was a large expense. Exotic would shoot donated horses then feed them to the tigers.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\">{{cite news |last1=Moor |first1=Robert |title=American Animals Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis. |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |agency=Intelligencer |publisher=Vox Media Network |date=September 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, 2017, Exotic's husband, Travis Maldonado, fatally shot himself in the head. The shooting occurred while the zoo was open and in front of an employee.<ref name=\"GHM\">{{cite news |last1=Keeping |first1=Juliana |title=Shooting death at Wynnewood zoo under investigation |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5567169/shooting-death-at-wynnewood-zoo-under-investigation |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |agency=The Oklahoman |publisher=Gatehouse Media |date=October 7, 2017}}</ref> The Garvin County Sheriff's office ruled that the shooting was accidental.<ref name=\"KXII\">{{cite news |title=Sheriff: Oklahoma zookeeper\u2019s husband accidentally shot self |url=https://www.kxii.com/content/news/-Sheriff-Oklahoma-zookeepers-husband-accidentally-shot-self-450267893.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 | agency=KXII News 12 |publisher=Associated Press |date=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest and conviction ===\nIn September 2018, Exotic was arrested and indicted by the FBI for attempting to hire a hitman to murder Carole Baskin, chief executive officer of Tampa animal sanctuary [[Big Cat Rescue]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Nolan|last1=Clay|first2=Josh|last2=Wallace|title=Joe Exotic, former Oklahoma gubernatorial candidate, indicted, accused in murder-for-hire plot|url=https://newsok.com/article/5607480/joe-exotic-former-oklahoma-gubernatorial-candidate-indicted-accused-in-murder-for-hire-plot|work=The Oklahoman|date=September 7, 2018|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref> Exotic was arrested and convicted on April 2, 2019<ref name=oklahoman2019 /> for two counts of [[murder-for-hire]], eight violations of the [[Lacey Act]] and nine of the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=\"oklahoman2019\"/> On January 22, 2020 he was sentenced to 22 years in federal prison.<ref name=\"ABC\"/>\n\n=== New ownership ===\nIn 2019, the subsequent owner of the zoo, Jeff Lowe, announced plans to close the zoo in Wynnewood and move the animals to a new location near [[Thackerville, Oklahoma]].<ref name=\"oklahoman2019\">{{cite news|first=Nolan|last=Clay|title=Joe Exotic found guilty in murder-for-hire case|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5627553/joe-exotic-found-guilty-in-murder-for-hire-case|work=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=April 3, 2019|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Documentary==\nThe 2020 [[Netflix]] original documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'' was centered on Joe Exotic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|url=https://www.netflix.com/title/81115994|publisher=Netflix|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Julie|last=Miller|title=Netflix's Wild Tiger King Is Your Next True Crime TV Obsession|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/03/netflix-tiger-king-trailer-joe-exotic|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe park received thousands of visitors following the release of the documentary. However, Oklahoma Governor [[Kevin Stitt]] required that all non-essential businesses close because of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. On March 31, 2020, the [[Garvin County, Oklahoma]] sheriff said the zoo had closed to visitors in compliance with the governor's order to shut down nonessential business.<ref name=\"GWZtempclosing\">{{Cite news |last=Yuhas |first=Alan and Cramer, Maria |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html |title=What Happened After 'Tiger King' |date=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=April 4, 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[https://email.nationalgeographic.com/H/2/v40000016fd42e8e529b5c766e96c660c0/dbc6062c-a4ba-4b33-ae3b-cb86112d1e17/HTML National Geographic article on Joe Exotic]\n*[https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/tigers-in-the-united-states-outnumber-those-in-the-wild-feature/?cmpid=org=ngp::mc=crm-email::src=ngp::cmp=editorial::add=Animals_20200123&rid=CC8D94CAC95F51BE9F5A4B4F2D84467D A study of captive tigers by National Geographic]\n\n{{Zoos of Oklahoma}}\n{{Tiger King}}\n\n[[Category:Roadside attractions in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Zoos in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Garvin County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Garvin County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1999]]\n", "name_user": "Chasethesky", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added Garold Wayne's last name, Schreibvogel)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greater_Wynnewood_Exotic_Animal_Park"}
{"title_page": "Shaoquett Moselmane", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| image =\n| caption       =\n| name=Shaoquett Moselmane\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of the New South Wales Legislative Council|MLC]]\n| office        = Member of [[Legislative Council of New South Wales]]\n| term_start    = 3 December 2009\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   = [[Henry Tsang]]\n| successor     =\n| constituency  = \n| majority      =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place   = Konin, [[Lebanon]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| party         = [[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Australian Labor Party]]\n| relations     =\n| spouse        = Mika Fukuta Moselmane\n| children      = Joseph Moselmane\n| residence     =\n| occupation    = Solicitor\n| alma_mater    = [[The University of Sydney]]<br>[[Macquarie University]]<br>[[University of New South Wales]] \n| religion      = [[Muslim]]<ref name =\"abc-twt\"/>\n| signature     =\n| website       =\n[http://www.shaoquettmoselmane.com Personal webpage]\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Shaoquett Chaher Moselmane''' (born 1965<ref name=maiden/>), an Australian politician, is a member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Council]] since 2009, representing the [[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Australian Labor Party]].\n\n==Early years and background==\nMoselmane was born in Konin, [[southern Lebanon]].<ref name=maiden/> He arrived in Australia from Lebanon in 1977 together with his parents, Chaher Mouslimani and Jawaher Mohanna Mouslimani, and ten other brothers and sisters. He attended Rockdale Public School and [[James Cook Boys Technology High School|James Cook Boys' High School]] before graduating with a Bachelor of Arts (politics and government administration) from the [[University of Sydney]]. Obtaining a [[Master degree]] in politics from [[Macquarie University]], Moselmane went on to complete a [[Bachelor of Laws]] from the [[University of New South Wales]].<ref name=maiden>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/member/files/50/Inaugural%20Speech.pdf |title=Inaugural Speech |work=[[Hansard]] |publisher=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] |date=25 February 2010 |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref> In 1999, Moselmane commenced practising law as a [[solicitor]].\n\nIn 1995, Moselmane was elected to [[City of Rockdale|Rockdale City Council]] in Sydney's south and served as mayor from 2001 to 2003, from 2005 to 2006, and again in 2009 until his appointment to the Legislative Council. Moselmane retired from Rockdale Council at the 2012 NSW Local Government Elections.<ref name=nswpl/>\n\n==Political career==\nMoselmane was appointed to the Legislative Council on 3 December 2009, to fill a vacancy created by the resignation of [[Henry Tsang]],<ref name=nswpl>{{cite NSW Parliament |id=50 |name=The Hon. Shaoquett Moselmane, MLC |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref> and is the first Muslim member of the New South Wales Parliament.<ref name =\"abc-twt\">{{cite news\n | title = New South Wales set to elect first Muslim MP\n | url = http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2009/s2750569.htm\n | work = The World Today\n | publisher = [[The Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n | date = 23 November 2009\n | accessdate = 2009-12-10\n | author = Santow, Simon\n }} \n</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Moselmane instituted the [[Multicultural and Indigenous Media Awards]],<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Not Enough Hands!\n  | date = 20 September 2012\n  | publisher =IndianLink\n  | url =http://www.indianlink.com.au/sydney-news/not-enough-hands/ }}</ref>\nand in June, 2014, he launched the [[National Indigenous Human Rights Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Conimos |first=Anna |date=9 July 2014 |title=Future Ancients |url=http://neoskosmos.com/news/en/Future-Ancients |newspaper=[[Neos Kosmos (newspaper)|Neos Kosmos]] }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Moselmane was one of three Labor MPs to vote with the [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal Party]] and [[National Party of Australia \u2013 NSW|National Party]] to block a bill to decriminalise [[abortion]] in the state.<ref>{{cite news |title=NSW Parliament votes to keep abortion in Crimes Act |work=Lawyers Weekly |url=https://www.lawyersweekly.com.au/careers/21089-nsw-parliament-votes-to-keep-abortion-in-crimes-act-2 |date=12 May 2017 |last=Coade |first=Melissa |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2019, Shaoquett Moselmane was elected as Assistant President of the NSW Legislative Council.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that Moselmane had hired a staffer who had been trained at the [[Chinese Academy of Governance]], a high-level training institution for officials of the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/you-must-be-a-potential-leader-labor-mp-s-staffer-links-to-china-s-communist-party-20190911-p52q99.html|title='You must be a potential leader': Labor MP's staffer links to China's Communist Party|last=Visentin|first=Lisa|date=2019-09-15|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Moselmane praised [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], for his \"unswerving leadership\" in responding to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Visentin|first=Lisa|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/unswerving-leadership-nsw-labor-mp-praises-china-s-coronavirus-response-20200330-p54fbg.html|title='Unswerving leadership': NSW Labor MP praises China's coronavirus response|date=March 30, 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Labor leader [[Jodi McKay]] subsequently criticised the comment as \"inappropriate\" while other legislators called for Moselmane's resignation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Visentin|first=Lisa|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/nsw-labor-leader-labels-mp-s-china-remarks-as-inappropriate-20200402-p54gdb.html|title=NSW Labor leader labels MP's China remarks as 'inappropriate'|date=April 2, 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an opinion piece written for the [[East China Normal University]], Moselmane also praised China's authorities and accused \"the obsolete scum of white Australia\" of fostering [[Sinophobia]] in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McKenzie|first=Nick|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/obsolete-scum-of-white-australia-behind-anti-chinese-sentiment-says-nsw-labor-mp-20200405-p54h9m.html|title='Obsolete scum of white Australia' behind anti-Chinese sentiment, says NSW Labor MP|date=April 6, 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NSWCurrentMLCs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moselmane, Shaoquett}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Australian city councillors]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Rockdale]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Macquarie University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n[[Category:Lebanese emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| image =\n| caption       =\n| name=Shaoquett Moselmane\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of the New South Wales Legislative Council|MLC]]\n| office        = Member of [[Legislative Council of New South Wales]]\n| term_start    = 3 December 2009\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   = [[Henry Tsang]]\n| successor     =\n| constituency  = \n| majority      =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place   = Konin, [[Lebanon]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| party         = [[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Australian Labor Party]]\n| relations     =\n| spouse        = Mika Fukuta Moselmane\n| children      = Joseph Moselmane\n| residence     =\n| occupation    = Solicitor\n| alma_mater    = [[The University of Sydney]]<br>[[Macquarie University]]<br>[[University of New South Wales]] \n| religion      = [[Muslim]]<ref name =\"abc-twt\"/>\n| signature     =\n| website       =\n[http://www.shaoquettmoselmane.com Personal webpage]\n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Shaoquett Chaher Moselmane''' (born 1965<ref name=maiden/>), an Australian politician, is a member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Council]] since 2009, representing the [[Australian Labor Party (New South Wales Branch)|Australian Labor Party]].\n\n==Early years and background==\nMoselmane was born in Konin, [[southern Lebanon]].<ref name=maiden/> He arrived in Australia from Lebanon in 1977 together with his parents, Chaher Mouslimani and Jawaher Mohanna Mouslimani, and ten other brothers and sisters. He attended Rockdale Public School and [[James Cook Boys Technology High School|James Cook Boys' High School]] before graduating with a Bachelor of Arts (politics and government administration) from the [[University of Sydney]]. Obtaining a [[Master degree]] in politics from [[Macquarie University]], Moselmane went on to complete a [[Bachelor of Laws]] from the [[University of New South Wales]].<ref name=maiden>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/member/files/50/Inaugural%20Speech.pdf |title=Inaugural Speech |work=[[Hansard]] |publisher=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] |date=25 February 2010 |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref> In 1999, Moselmane commenced practicing law as a solicitor.\n\nIn 1995, Moselmane was elected to [[City of Rockdale|Rockdale City Council]] in Sydney's south and served as mayor from 2001 to 2003, from 2005 to 2006, and again in 2009 until his appointment to the Legislative Council. Moselmane retired from Rockdale Council at the 2012 NSW Local Government Elections.<ref name=nswpl/>\n\n==Political career==\nMoselmane was appointed to the Legislative Council on 3 December 2009, to fill a vacancy created by the resignation of [[Henry Tsang]],<ref name=nswpl>{{cite NSW Parliament |id=50 |name=The Hon. Shaoquett Moselmane, MLC |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref> and is the first Muslim member of the New South Wales Parliament.<ref name =\"abc-twt\">{{cite news\n | title = New South Wales set to elect first Muslim MP\n | url = http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2009/s2750569.htm\n | work = The World Today\n | publisher = [[The Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n | date = 23 November 2009\n | accessdate = 2009-12-10\n | author = Santow, Simon\n }} \n</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Moselmane instituted the [[Multicultural and Indigenous Media Awards]],<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Not Enough Hands!\n  | date = 20 September 2012\n  | publisher =IndianLink\n  | url =http://www.indianlink.com.au/sydney-news/not-enough-hands/ }}</ref>\nand in June, 2014, he launched the [[National Indigenous Human Rights Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Conimos |first=Anna |date=9 July 2014 |title=Future Ancients |url=http://neoskosmos.com/news/en/Future-Ancients |newspaper=[[Neos Kosmos (newspaper)|Neos Kosmos]] }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Moselmane was one of three Labor MPs to vote with the [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal Party]] and [[National Party of Australia \u2013 NSW|National Party]] to block a bill to decriminalise [[abortion]] in the state.<ref>{{cite news |title=NSW Parliament votes to keep abortion in Crimes Act |work=Lawyers Weekly |url=https://www.lawyersweekly.com.au/careers/21089-nsw-parliament-votes-to-keep-abortion-in-crimes-act-2 |date=12 May 2017 |last=Coade |first=Melissa |accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2019, Shaoquett Moselmane was elected as Assistant President of the NSW Legislative Council.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that Moselmane had hired a staffer who had been trained at the [[Chinese Academy of Governance]], a high-level training institution for officials of the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/you-must-be-a-potential-leader-labor-mp-s-staffer-links-to-china-s-communist-party-20190911-p52q99.html|title='You must be a potential leader': Labor MP's staffer links to China's Communist Party|last=Visentin|first=Lisa|date=2019-09-15|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Moselmane praised [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], for his \"unswerving leadership\" in responding to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Visentin|first=Lisa|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/unswerving-leadership-nsw-labor-mp-praises-china-s-coronavirus-response-20200330-p54fbg.html|title='Unswerving leadership': NSW Labor MP praises China's coronavirus response|date=March 30, 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Labor leader [[Jodi McKay]] subsequently criticised the comment as \"inappropriate\" while other legislators called for Moselmane's resignation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Visentin|first=Lisa|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/nsw-labor-leader-labels-mp-s-china-remarks-as-inappropriate-20200402-p54gdb.html|title=NSW Labor leader labels MP's China remarks as 'inappropriate'|date=April 2, 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an opinion piece written for the [[East China Normal University]], Moselmane also praised China's authorities and accused \"the obsolete scum of white Australia\" of fostering [[Sinophobia]] in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McKenzie|first=Nick|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/obsolete-scum-of-white-australia-behind-anti-chinese-sentiment-says-nsw-labor-mp-20200405-p54h9m.html|title='Obsolete scum of white Australia' behind anti-Chinese sentiment, says NSW Labor MP|date=April 6, 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NSWCurrentMLCs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moselmane, Shaoquett}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Australian city councillors]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Rockdale]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Macquarie University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n[[Category:Lebanese emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lucius Winslow", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly years and background", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaoquett_Moselmane"}
{"title_page": "Dana Hills High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| image = [[File:Puff Bar -BANANA ICE.jpg|thumb|Banana Ice Puff Bar]]\n| image_size = 250px\n| name = Dana Hills High School\n| type = Public School\n| streetaddress = 33333 Golden Lantern\n| city = [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]]\n| state = [[California]]\n| country = USA\n| zipcode = 92629\n| url = https://dhhs.schoolloop.com/\n| established = 1972\n| opened = 1973\n| grades = 9-12\n| enrollment = 2,588 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0607440&SchoolPageNum=2&ID=060744000689 Dana Hills High]</ref>\n| ratio = 24.91<ref name=NCES></ref>\n| faculty = 103.91 (FTE)<ref name=NCES></ref>\n| principal = Brad Baker\n| team name = Dolphins\n| yearbook = The Mast\n| newspaper = [http://www.dhhsthepaper.com THE PAPER]\n| conference = [[CIF-SS]]; [[Sea View League]] [[South Coast League (California)|South Coast League]]\n| colors = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|silver|border=darkgray}} Blue & Silver\n| district = [[Capistrano Unified School District]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Dana Hills High School''' is a high school in [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]], [[California]]. It is one of the oldest high schools in [[South Orange County]], having opened in 1973. The school's enrollment of nearly 3,000 students is drawn from the nearby communities of [[Laguna Niguel, California|Laguna Niguel]], [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]], [[Capistrano Beach, California|Capistrano Beach]], and [[San Juan Capistrano, California|San Juan Capistrano]].\n\nWhen Dana Hills was built in 1972\u201373, the area was an unincorporated area of Orange County.  The school was named for its hilltop location over the unincorporated village of Dana Point, as well as the tip of the hill projecting south into the Pacific Ocean as the Dana Point headland.  The school later became a part of the City of Dana Point, when the city was incorporated in 1989.\n\nDana Hills now has over {{convert|155839|sqft|m2}} in permanent buildings. The principal is Brad Baker.\n\n==STAR Testing==\nDana Hills' [[Academic Performance Index]] (API) for the year of 2007 was 824. \n\n===Recent scores===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:25%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!API\n!Growth\n|-\n| 2011 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/Acnt2011/2011GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2011 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov (2012-08-13). Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 855|| 58\n|-\n| 2010 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/AcntRpt2010/2010GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2010 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov (2011-10-05). Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 848|| 8\n|-\n| 2009 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/AcntRpt2009/2009GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2009 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov. Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 839|| 0\n|-\n| 2008 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/AcntRpt2008/2008GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2008 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov (2010-03-26). Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 899|| 9\n|-\n| 2007 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/AcntRpt2007/2007GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2007 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov (2008-08-20). Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 824|| 8\n|-\n| 2006 <ref>http://www3.cde.ca.gov/researchfiles/api/api06gtx.zip</ref>|| 816|| 5\n|-\n| 2005 <ref>http://www3.cde.ca.gov/researchfiles/api/api05gtx.zip</ref>|| 811|| 43\n|-\n| 2004 <ref>http://www3.cde.ca.gov/researchfiles/api/api04gtx.zip</ref>|| 768|| 18\n|-\n| 2003 <ref>http://www3.cde.ca.gov/researchfiles/api/api03gtx.zip</ref>|| 749|| 0\n|}\n\n==Advanced Placement==\nDana Hills offers a wide array of [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) classes. These AP classes include Calculus AB, Calculus BC, Statistics, Biology, Chemistry, Environmental Science, Literature, Language and Composition, Music Theory, Art History, Psychology, Spanish IV, French IV, European History, United States History, World History, Government/Politics, and Computer Science A. All AP classes offer a \u201cgrade bump\u201d making a 5.0 GPA possible in that class exclusively.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Newspaper==\nThe Dana Hills newspaper, originally called the Dolphin Dispatch from 1973 to 1992, now simply known as The Paper (stylized as \"THE PAPER\"), is produced by a staff of roughly 20 students. Ten newspapers are produced each school year. It features five sections: news, feature, opinion, entertainment, and sports.\n\nIn May 2019, the newspaper went digital with a new website ([http://www.dhhsthepaper.com www.dhhsthepaper.com]) created by a staff member.\n\n==HMO==\nDana Hills has a junior medical program, the Health and Medical Occupations Academy. The academy is for those who wish to study or pursue a career in medicine, as it prepares students for higher education in the medical field. Participants are involved in field trips, hospital duties, and view medical procedures as they are performed.\n\n==SOCSA==\n\nThe South Orange County School of the Arts (SOCSA), a part of Dana Hills High School, is a visual and performing arts academy for students within the Capistrano Unified School District. Conceived in 1989 by a group of parents, teachers and administrators, the academy was chartered by the District on November 20, 1995.  The pilot program at Dana Hills High School was launched in the Spring semester of 1996.\n\nIn October 2000, the SOCSA Foundation was formed to raise funds to support the SOCSA Academy.  In the fall of 2015, the Friends of SOCSA was formed as a replacement non-profit to support the SOCSA Academy.\n\n[http://www.socsarts.org/ SOCSA website]\n\n==Marine Ecology Program==\nOne of Dana Hills' science courses is the Marine Ecology program, which offers a full year of marine science covering both the physical and biological sciences of the ocean and how they work together to form a working Ecosystem. Examples of some of the subjects taught during the class include plate tectonics, waves and tides, ocean currents, sand, algae, plankton, marine mammals, echinoderms, and fish. One of the most well-known traditions of the class is the annual Baja field study. In this field study, students, parents, teachers, and past alumni of the class travel down to Baja, California for a week, usually in May. The purpose of this field study is to apply what the students have learned that year in the class and see it in its natural environment, outside of a conventional laboratory setting. The Baja field study is unique only to that of Dana Hills, and essentially offered nowhere else in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n<!-- Only legitimately famous or well-known people, preferably with a Wikipedia entry -->\n* [[Dana Brown]], film maker\n* [[Ian McCall (fighter)|Ian McCall]], wrestler; professional [[mixed martial artist]], retired [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] Flyweight contender<ref>{{cite web|title=Ian McCall UFC Bio|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Ian-McCall|accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref>\n* [[Nicole Brown Simpson]], former wife of Heisman Trophy winner/ex-NFL player and actor [[O. J. Simpson]]\n* [[Melinda Clarke]] of ''[[The O.C.]]''\n* Kevin Page of [[Something Corporate]]\n* [[Brian Ireland]] of [[Something Corporate]]\n* [[Andrew McMahon]], lead singer of Jack's Mannequin, Something Corporate, and Andrew McMahon In the Wilderness\n* [[Scott Covington]], NFL quarterback for the St. Louis Rams and Cincinnati Bengals\n* Justin South of [[Augustana (band)|Augustana]]\n* [[Seth Etherton]], Major League Baseball pitcher for the Anaheim Angels and Cincinnati Reds\n* [[Bao Quach]], wrestler; professional [[mixed martial arts|MMA]] fighter<ref>{{cite web|title=Bao Quach MMA Bio|url=http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Bao-Quach-494|accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref>\n* [[Tanner Scheppers]], MLB pitcher for Texas Rangers\n* Kyle Straka of [[The Growlers]]\n* [[Fredy Montero]] professional soccer player\n* [[Erik Apple]]  Professional MMA fighter and from the movie ''Warrior'' (2011), formerly competing in [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Erik Apple MMA Bio|url=http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Erik-Apple-7378|accessdate=2014-01-01}}</ref>\n* [[Jose Cortez]], center for Greek Team Athens 2003\u20132009\n* [[Charlotte Drury]], national and international champion trampolinist\n*[[Anthony Cumia]], one half of the former ''[[Opie and Anthony]]'' radio show and host of ''[[The Anthony Cumia Show]]'' on [[Compound Media]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://dhhs.schoolloop.com/ Official website]\n*[http://www.greatschools.net/modperl/browse_school/ca/3649 School Profile]\n*[https://www.dhhsthepaper.com/ THE PAPER]\n*[http://www.socsarts.org/ SOCSA Website]\n{{Orange County, California Schools}}\n{{Coord|33|28|40|N|117|42|02|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:High schools in Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| image = DanaHills.JPG\n| image_size = 250px\n| name = Dana Hills High School\n| type = Public School\n| streetaddress = 33333 Golden Lantern\n| city = [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]]\n| state = [[California]]\n| country = USA\n| zipcode = 92629\n| url = https://dhhs.schoolloop.com/\n| established = 1972\n| opened = 1973\n| grades = 9-12\n| enrollment = 2,588 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0607440&SchoolPageNum=2&ID=060744000689 Dana Hills High]</ref>\n| ratio = 24.91<ref name=NCES></ref>\n| faculty = 103.91 (FTE)<ref name=NCES></ref>\n| principal = Brad Baker\n| team name = Dolphins\n| yearbook = The Mast\n| newspaper = [http://www.dhhsthepaper.com THE PAPER]\n| conference = [[CIF-SS]]; [[Sea View League]] [[South Coast League (California)|South Coast League]]\n| colors = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|silver|border=darkgray}} Blue & Silver\n| district = [[Capistrano Unified School District]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Dana Hills High School''' is a high school in [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]], [[California]]. It is one of the oldest high schools in [[South Orange County]], having opened in 1973. The school's enrollment of nearly 3,000 students is drawn from the nearby communities of [[Laguna Niguel, California|Laguna Niguel]], [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]], [[Capistrano Beach, California|Capistrano Beach]], and [[San Juan Capistrano, California|San Juan Capistrano]].\n\nWhen Dana Hills was built in 1972\u201373, the area was an unincorporated area of Orange County.  The school was named for its hilltop location over the unincorporated village of Dana Point, as well as the tip of the hill projecting south into the Pacific Ocean as the Dana Point headland.  The school later became a part of the City of Dana Point, when the city was incorporated in 1989.\n\nDana Hills now has over {{convert|155839|sqft|m2}} in permanent buildings. The principal is Brad Baker.\n\n==STAR Testing==\nDana Hills' [[Academic Performance Index]] (API) for the year of 2007 was 824. \n\n===Recent scores===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:25%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!API\n!Growth\n|-\n| 2011 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/Acnt2011/2011GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2011 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov (2012-08-13). Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 855|| 58\n|-\n| 2010 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/AcntRpt2010/2010GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2010 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov (2011-10-05). Retrieved on 2012-10-11.</ref>|| 848|| 8\n|-\n| 2009 <ref>[http://api.cde.ca.gov/AcntRpt2009/2009GrowthSch.aspx?allcds=30664643038569 2009 Growth API School Report \u2013 Dana Hills High]. Api.cde.ca.gov. Retrieved on 2012-10-11.<