ution]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptists]]\n[[Category:United States congressional aides]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:University of Kentucky College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Louisville alumni]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n", "name_user": "Trevdna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelationship with Trump administration", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitch_McConnell"}
{"title_page": "Kongu Vellalar", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox caste\n| caste_name             = Kongu Vellalar\n| image                  =\n| caption                = \n| region                 = [[Kongu Nadu]]\n| religions              = \n| country                = India\n| state                  = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| populated_states       = Major population in [[Tamil Nadu]]; Minor population in [[Karnataka]] and [[Kerala]]; diaspora in [[United Kingdom]], the [[United States]], [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], [[South Africa]] and [[Sri Lanka]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Gounder-consolidation-could-pose-headache-to-major-parties/articleshow/4557663.cms?referral=PM | title=Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties | first=Jayaraj | last=Sivan | newspaper=The Times of India | date=21 May 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2016 }}</ref>\n| languages              = [[Tamil language|Tamil]] ([[Kongu Tamil]])\n| classification         = [[Backward Class]] \n| related                = [[Vellalar]]\n}}\n\n'''Kongu Vellalar''' is a sub-caste of [[Vellalar]] community found in the western region of [[Tamil Nadu]], which is known as [[Kongu Nadu]].\nThe Kongu Vellala Gounders were classified as a [[Forward Caste]] (General class) at the time of [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] but they successfully requested to be reclassified as a [[Backward Class]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article277921.ece | newspaper=The Hindu| title=Looking to create a Kongu stronghold | date=8 May 2009 | first=K.V. | last=Prasad | accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThey are also known by names such as ''Bupaalan'', ''Kudiyaanavar'' and ''Vivasaayi'', and use the title [[Gounder]] as a caste appellation in their personal names.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ez9uAAAAMAAJ|title=Salem cyclopedia: a cultural and historical dictionary of Salem District, Tamil Nadu|last=Rajannan|first=Busnagi|last2=India)|first2=Institute of Kongu Studies (Salem|date=1992|publisher=Institute of Kongu Studies|page=340|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe Kongu Vellalar were inhabitants of the [[Kongu Nadu|Kongu country]] since atleast the 10th century CE.<ref>{{cite book|title=Salem cyclopedia: a cultural and historical dictionary of Salem District, Tamil Nadu|author=Busnagi Rajannan, Institute of Kongu Studies (Salem, India)|publisher=Institute of Kongu Studies, 1992|page=5}}</ref>\n\nThe Vellalars of Kongu region came to be known as Kongu Vellalar or Gounder, though both the names have also been treated separately in some regions.<ref>{{cite book |title=Historical Dictionary of the Tamils|first=Vijaya |last=Ramaswamy |page=303 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2007 |isbn=9780810864450 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H4q0DHGMcjEC}}</ref>\n\nThe community plays a significant role in the political and economic life of the Kongu Nadu region.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-05-21/chennai/28179309_1_poll-observers-assembly-polls-poll-eve Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties \u2013 Times Of India<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Rahul-keen-to-test-western-belt-/articleshow/7498031.cms?referral=PM | title=Rahul keen to test western belt | newspaper=The Times of India | first=Jaya | last=Menon | date=15 February 2011 | accessdate=22 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Wedding===\nThe community has its own style of marriage ceremony. The ceremony is led by person called an Arumbukarar or Arumaikkarar.<ref>{{cite book | title = Peasant Society of Konku: A Study of right and left subastes in South India | first = Brenda | last = Beck | publisher = University of British Columbia Press, Vancouver | year = 1972 | page = [https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/299 299] | ISBN = 0-7748-0014-3 | url = https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/299 }}</ref> A long song composed by a Poet and Tamil Saint [[Kambar (poet)|Kambar]], called \"Mangala Valthu\", is usually sung.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/Kambar-Kongunadus-Friend-or-Foe/2015/09/20/article3037320.ece |title=Kambar, Kongunadu's Friend or Foe? |first=B. Meenakshi |last=Sundaram |work=New Indian Express |date=20 September 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-12}}</ref> In the wedding ceremony, the brother of the bride and sister of the groom play significant roles.<ref>{{cite book | title = Peasant Society of Konku: A Study of right and left subastes in South India | first = Brenda | last = Beck | publisher = University of British Columbia Press, Vancouver | year = 1972 | page = [https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/240 240] | ISBN = 0-7748-0014-3 | url = https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/240 }}</ref>\n\n===Thaali===\nA [[Mangala sutra|Mangala Sutra]] is a necklace that the groom ties around the bride's neck in the [[Indian subcontinent]], in a ceremony called ''Mangalya Dharanam'', which identifies her as a married woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hinduism.about.com/od/matrimonial1/a/mangalsutra.htm|title=Mangalsutra Necklace \u2013 Hindu Symbol of Love & Marriage|author=Subhamoy Das|work=About.com Religion & Spirituality|accessdate=8 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513102744/http://hinduism.about.com/od/matrimonial1/a/mangalsutra.htm|archivedate=13 May 2016}}</ref> It is called, ''thaali'' ({{Lang|ta|\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbf}}), ''maangalyam'' ({{Lang|ta|\u0bae\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd}}) in [[Tamil language|Tamil]]. The traditional Kongu Vellala Gounder Thaali is shown below:\n<gallery>\nFile:A- thaali koundars.jpg|Kongu Vellala Gounder Thaali\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Vellalar]]\n[[Category:Gounder]]\n[[Category:Kongu Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{infobox caste\n| caste_name             = Kongu Vellalar\n| image                  =\n| caption                = \n| region                 = [[Kongu  Nadu]]\n| religions              = \n| country                = India\n| state                  = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| populated_states       = Major population in [[Tamil Nadu]]; Minor population in [[Karnataka]] and [[Kerala]]; diaspora in [[United Kingdom]], the [[United States]], [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], [[South Africa]] and [[Sri Lanka]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Gounder-consolidation-could-pose-headache-to-major-parties/articleshow/4557663.cms?referral=PM | title=Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties | first=Jayaraj | last=Sivan | newspaper=The Times of India | date=21 May 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2016 }}</ref>\n| languages              = [[Tamil language|Tamil]] ([[Kongu Tamil]])\n| classification         = [[Backward Class]] \n| related                = [[Vellalar]]\n}}\n\n'''Kongu Vellalar''' is a sub-caste of [[Vellalar]] community found in the western region of [[Tamil Nadu]], which is known as [[Kongu Nadu]].\nThe Kongu Vellala Gounders were classified as a [[Forward Caste]] (General class) at the time of [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] but they successfully requested to be reclassified as a [[Backward Class]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article277921.ece | newspaper=The Hindu | title=Looking to create a Kongu stronghold | date=8 May 2009 | first=K.V. | last=Prasad | accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThey are also known by names such as ''Bupaalan'', ''Kudiyaanavar'' and ''Vivasaayi'', and use the title [[Gounder]] as a caste appellation in their personal names.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ez9uAAAAMAAJ|title=Salem cyclopedia: a cultural and historical dictionary of Salem District, Tamil Nadu|last=Rajannan|first=Busnagi|last2=India)|first2=Institute of Kongu Studies (Salem|date=1992|publisher=Institute of Kongu Studies|year=|isbn=|location=|page=340|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe Kongu Vellalar were inhabitants of the [[Kongu Nadu|Kongu country]] since atleast the 10th century CE.<ref>{{cite book|title=Salem cyclopedia: a cultural and historical dictionary of Salem District, Tamil Nadu|author=Busnagi Rajannan, Institute of Kongu Studies (Salem, India)|publisher=Institute of Kongu Studies, 1992|page=5}}</ref>\n\nThe Vellalars of Kongu region came to be known as Kongu Vellalar or Gounder, though both the names have also been treated separately in some regions.<ref>{{cite book |title=Historical Dictionary of the Tamils|first=Vijaya |last=Ramaswamy |page=303 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2007 |isbn=9780810864450 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H4q0DHGMcjEC}}</ref>\n\nThe community plays a significant role in the political and economic life of the Kongu Nadu region.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-05-21/chennai/28179309_1_poll-observers-assembly-polls-poll-eve Gounder consolidation could pose headache to major parties - Times Of India<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Rahul-keen-to-test-western-belt-/articleshow/7498031.cms?referral=PM | title=Rahul keen to test western belt | newspaper=The Times of India | first=Jaya | last=Menon | date=15 February 2011 | accessdate=22 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Wedding===\nThe community has its own style of marriage ceremony. The ceremony is led by person called an Arumbukarar or Arumaikkarar.<ref>{{cite book | title = Peasant Society of Konku: A Study of right and left subastes in South India | first = Brenda | last = Beck | publisher = University of British Columbia Press, Vancouver | year = 1972 | page = [https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/299 299] | ISBN = 0-7748-0014-3 | url = https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/299 }}</ref> A long song composed by a Poet and Tamil Saint [[Kambar (poet)|Kambar]], called \"Mangala Valthu\", is usually sung.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/Kambar-Kongunadus-Friend-or-Foe/2015/09/20/article3037320.ece |title=Kambar, Kongunadu's Friend or Foe? |first=B. Meenakshi |last=Sundaram |work=New Indian Express |date=20 September 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-12}}</ref> In the wedding ceremony, the brother of the bride and sister of the groom play significant roles.<ref>{{cite book | title = Peasant Society of Konku: A Study of right and left subastes in South India | first = Brenda | last = Beck | publisher = University of British Columbia Press, Vancouver | year = 1972 | page = [https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/240 240] | ISBN = 0-7748-0014-3 | url = https://archive.org/details/peasantsocietyin0000beck/page/240 }}</ref>\n===Thaali===\nA [[Mangala sutra|Mangala Sutra]] is a necklace that the groom ties around the bride's neck in the [[Indian subcontinent]], in a ceremony called ''Mangalya Dharanam'', which identifies her as a married woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hinduism.about.com/od/matrimonial1/a/mangalsutra.htm|title=Mangalsutra Necklace - Hindu Symbol of Love & Marriage|author=Subhamoy Das|work=About.com Religion & Spirituality|accessdate=8 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513102744/http://hinduism.about.com/od/matrimonial1/a/mangalsutra.htm|archivedate=13 May 2016}}</ref> It is called, ''thaali'' ({{Lang|ta|\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbf}}), ''maangalyam'' ({{Lang|ta|\u0bae\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd}}) in  [[Tamil language|Tamil]]. The traditional Kongu Vellala Gounder Thaali is shown below:\n<gallery>\nFile:A- thaali koundars.jpg|Kongu Vellala Gounder Thaali\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Vellalar]]\n[[Category:Gounder]]\n[[Category:Kongu Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kongu_Vellalar"}
